LI.
When <persName id="#caesar">Caesar</persName> had attacked warlike nations and had conquered them with great hazard, and when it was the opinion that he had fallen upon the <personGrp id="#germans">Germans</personGrp> even after a truce had been made, and had destroyed three hundred thousand of them, the rest indeed were promising to <persName id="#the_people">the people</persName> to offer sacrifices for the victory, but <persName id="#cato">Cato</persName> urged that they should give up <persName id="#caesar">Caesar</persName> to those who had been wronged, and should not turn the guilt upon themselves nor allow it to fall on the state.
