Yet he found not <persName id="#cato">Cato</persName>'s zeal dulled by this; for it is told that when <persName id="#pompeius">Pompeius</persName> was urging <persName id="#his_troops">his troops</persName> to a battle before <persName id="#dyrrachium">Dyrrachium</persName> and bidding each of <persName id="#the_commanders">the commanders</persName> say something and to encourage <persName id="#the_men">the men</persName>, <persName id="#the_soldiers">the soldiers</persName> heard them with listlessness and silence; but when <persName id="#cato">Cato</persName>, after the rest, had gone through all the topics derived from philosophy that were suitable to the occasion to be said about liberty and virtue, and death and good fame, with great emotion on his part, and finally addressed himself to invoke <persName id="#the_gods">the gods</persName> as being there present and watching over the struggle on behalf of their country, there was so loud an acclamation and so great a movement in <persName id="#the_whole_army">the whole army</persName> thus excited, that <persName id="#all_the_commanders">all the commanders</persName> hastened to the contest full of hopes.
